Creating a Sense of Urgency A while back I had this girlfriend. We had a lot of fun, but she was hesitant to commit to me. No matter what I tried, she just wouldn&rsquo;t become &ldquo;official.&rdquo;
Then, there was this other time—with another girlfriend—and I was the one having a hard time committing to her. We had a great time together, all systems go, but I couldn&rsquo;t help but wonder what else was out there&hellip;
In both relationships, a committment was finally made. But SOMETHING WAS NEEDED TO. Can you guess what it was? I&rsquo;ll tell you.
A breakup.
And both times the dumper came crawling back.
When we feel like we might lose something—especially when we perceive that thing as being good for us—the game changes. Suddenly, it&rsquo;s time to shit or get off the pot. And we might just realize we have to shit real bad.
A feeling of scarcity is a powerful motivator—one you&rsquo;re wise to exploit in every piece of copy you write. I&rsquo;ll tell you why.
Because even after the perfect pitch, an unbelievable offer, people won&rsquo;t take action. They&rsquo;ll want to think it over. They&rsquo;ll hem and haw. They&rsquo;ll move on. So you have to find a way to spur them into action. Otherwise&hellip;
They need to be tipped over the edge
They&rsquo;ll probably find themselves another boyfriend or girlfriend&hellip;
Stoke the fire with the fear of loss. Give your prospects a reason to buy now. Do it every time. The possibilities for doing so are limited only by your imagination.
Here are a few examples to get you started.
Swipes more scarcity stuff:
&ldquo;I screwed up, the price is supposed yto be 69 bucks, not 49, but if you respodnd before Friday, you can have it for 49.&rdquo;
If you take something people want, and suddenly lower the price, they will buy it.
This is specific scarcity&hellip;
I have something for sale. It normally costs $750K. I&rsquo;ll sell it now for $150K. (Value/Greed) Why? (Tell them why.) Because someone left a huge deposit and bailed. It&rsquo;s the missing person sale. You cover the rest and we&rsquo;re all good here. (Scarcity&mdash;once only. Greed.)

&ldquo;Details lend a sense of reality to even the most preposterous statements.&rdquo;
After you write your copy, go back through and make it more specific.
Be specific in your explanations of why things are and how they work.
&ldquo;New dentists everywhere use and recommend CapSnap toothpase.&rdquo; vs&hellip;
&ldquo;92 percent of dentists use and recommend&hellip;&rdquo;
There are 72,000 nerve endings in the bottom of your feet. vs Your feet are filled with nerve endings.
There are 242 miles of blood vessels in your body.
Show the exact cost of an ad then the exact cost of a product to prove you aren&rsquo;t making any money&hellip; but let them figure that out (mental engagement) * &ldquo;BluBlocker sunglasses let you see clearer, sharper, and with more definition.&rdquo; vs&hellip;
HOw they do that (check the ad).

Lower the Bar to Entry Get a yes.
An invitation they can say yes to.
The #1 thing to do is to make it as easy as possible for the prospect to commit to a purchase, regardless of home small that purchase may be. Once they do, they playing field has been changed.
Simple, small, inline with their needs.
Then add the upsells. This ties into consistency.
You want frieds with that? Floormats? Sell the first for $5, the rest for $19.95 a piece &ldquo;MeetCute is a creative writing guide designed to unleach your creativity&hellip; in less time than it takes you to drink 2 (maybe 3) cups of coffee.&rdquo;
&ldquo;An afternoon-sized guide that will teach you how to use cold email to get anything you want.&rdquo;
&ldquo;&hellip; in less than an afternoon.&rdquo;
